ani|first=Nicholas|date=2018|title=The tombs of the Palaiologan emperors|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/byzantine-and-modern-greek-studies/article/tombs-of-the-palaiologan-emperors/C5079928DCB842457C4BA712151A15F8|journal=Byzantine and Modern Greek Studies|volume=42|issue=2|pages=237\u2013260|ref=CITEREFMelvani2018|via=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Miller|first=William|title=Essays on the Latin Orient|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1921|isbn=|location=Cambridge|pages=|chapter=Miscellanea from the Near East: Balkan Exiles in Rome|oclc=457893641|ref=CITEREFMiller1921}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Nicol|first=Donald M.|title=The Immortal Emperor: The Life and Legend of Constantine Palaiologos, Last Emperor of the Romans|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1992|isbn=978-0511583698|location=Cambridge|pages=|ref=CITEREFNicol1992}}\n*{{Cite book|last=David|first=Potter|title=A History of France, 1460\u20131560: The Emergence of a Nation State|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=1995|isbn=978-0312124809|location=New York|pages=|ref=CITEREFPotter1995}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Runciman|first=Steven|title=The Fall of Constantinople 1453|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1969|isbn=978-0521398329|location=Cambridge|pages=|ref=CITEREFRunciman1969|orig-year=1965}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Setton|first=Kenneth M.|title=The Papacy and the Levant (1204\u20131571): Volume II: The Fifteenth Century|publisher=The American Philosophical Society|year=1997|isbn=978-0871691279|location=Philadelphia|pages=|ref=CITEREFSetton1978|orig-year=1978|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=0Sz2VYI0l1IC&pg=PA513&lpg=PA513&dq=%22Fernando%22+%22Despot+of+the+Morea%22&source=bl&ots=4zWq2D8YwO&sig=ACfU3U2lKQMzwOd_R_q9LicPXZoYXkghRw&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwit7bXKy-LoAhWQjosKHQvBB8MQ6AEwAXoECAwQLA#v=onepage&q=%22Fernando%22%20%22Despot%20of%20the%20Morea%22&f=false}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia | last1=Trapp | first1= Erich | last2=Beyer  | first2=Hans-Veit | last3=Kaplaneres | first3=Sokrates | last4=Leontiadis | first4=Ioannis | title=21342. {{lang|grc|\u03a0\u03b1\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03af\u03bd\u03b1 \u0391\u1f30\u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03bd\u03b1}} | encyclopedia=[[Prosopographisches Lexikon der Palaiologenzeit]] | volume=9 | pages= | publisher=Verlag der \u00d6sterreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften | location=Vienna | year=1989 | language = German|date=|ref=CITEREFTrappBeyerKaplaneresLeontiadis1989}}\n*{{The Latin Renovatio of Byzantium|chapter=The Imperial Ideology|pages=61\u2013101}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Palaiologos]] dynasty|17 January|1453|June|1502}}\n{{s-pre|}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[Constantine XI Palaiologos]]}}\n{{s-ttl| rows = 2 | title=[[List of Byzantine emperors|Emperor of Constantinople]]|years={{circa}} 1480\u20131494<br>1498\u20131502}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Charles VIII of France]]}}\n{{s-bef| before=Charles VIII of France}}\n{{s-aft|after=<small>Titles willed to the [[Catholic Monarchs]]</small>}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[Thomas Palaiologos]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title=[[Despot of the Morea]]|years=1465\u20131502}}\n{{s-aft|after=<small>Claimed by Fernando Palaiologos and [[Constantine Komnenos Arianites]]</small>}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palaiologos, Andreas}}\n[[Category:1453 births]]\n[[Category:1502 deaths]]\n[[Category:15th-century Byzantine people]]\n[[Category:16th-century Byzantine people]]\n[[Category:Palaiologos dynasty|Andreas]]\n[[Category:Greek Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Byzantine pretenders]]\n[[Category:Burials at St. Peter's Basilica]]\n", "name_user": "Ichthyovenator", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTravels and sale of the imperial title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andreas_Palaiologos"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea", "text_new": "{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 pandemic in North Korea}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case = \n| location = [[North Korea]]\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| arrival_date =\n| image = \n| caption = \n| recovery_cases = \n| deaths =\n| confirmed_cases = 0 (disputed)\n| suspected_cases =\n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\n{{Politics of North Korea|width=22.0em}}\n\nThere are no officially confirmed cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[North Korea]], although South Korean sources say that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the pandemic]] is steadily affecting the country. The virus is more likely to have come into North Korea from [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]], where the virus originates, than from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]]. The [[China\u2013North Korea border|Chinese-North Korean border]] restrictions are more relaxed than the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone|heavily militarized border]] between North and South Korea. However, suspected COVID-19 cases in the two Chinese provinces ([[Liaoning]] and [[Jilin]]) bordering North Korea have been low.<ref name=\"Who Knows\">{{Cite web |title=Who Knows How Many Virus Cases North Korea Has. It Says Zero |last1=Wainer |first1=David |last2=Lee |first2=Jihye |work=Bloomberg.com |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/north-korea-s-official-virus-tally-zero-experts-aren-t-so-sure }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nNorth Korea is an impoverished country with a weak healthcare system and [[Sanctions against North Korea|is subject to sanctions]], making it vulnerable in the event of an outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Korea says detected North Korea missile fire 'inapproriate' amid coronavirus |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/21/north-korea-fired-suspected-short-range-missiles-south-korea-says.html |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> There is concern that widespread malnutrition could worsen the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> North Korean public health official Pak Myong Su said that if the disease spread in North Korea, \"a serious disaster could not be avoided\".<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\"/>\n\nDiplomatically and economically isolated,<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> the country borders China, the starting point of the pandemic, which is North Korea's closest ally, most important trading partner, and a source of tourists.<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/><ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\">{{cite news |last1=Sang-Hun |first1=Choe |title=North Korea Claims No Coronavirus Cases. Can It Be Trusted? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/world/asia/north-korea-coronavirus.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korea's government is secretive and the media are tightly controlled, making it hard for outside observers to determine what is really going on in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\nHistorically, North Korea has cut off travel in the face of epidemics abroad, for instance during the [[2014 Ebola epidemic]].<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> Moreover, the country has had success in disease eradication in the past; it reportedly eliminated [[measles]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Minal K. |title=Progress Toward Regional Measles Elimination \u2014 Worldwide, 2000\u20132018 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/68/wr/mm6848a1.htm |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |date=2019 |language=en-us |doi=10.15585/mmwr.mm6848a1}}</ref><ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> North Korea's government is highly [[authoritarian]] and maintains strong control over the country, which experts anticipated could help in enforcing disease control measures such as [[social distancing]].<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Why North Korea's healthcare sector is better equipped than many believe |url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/why-north-koreas-healthcare-sector-is-better-equipped-than-many-believe/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=NK News - North Korea News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> North Korea also has a large number of doctors, though they are less skilled and equipped than their Western counterparts, and a high level of public hygiene.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why North Korea's healthcare sector is better equipped than many believe |url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/why-north-koreas-healthcare-sector-is-better-equipped-than-many-believe/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=NK News - North Korea News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\n[[File:Masikryong-Hotel-and-Lift.jpg|200px|thumb|left|[[Masikryong Ski Resort]], a popular ski resort in North Korea. Due to the outbreak of the virus, ski resorts and spas in North Korea have been closed.]]\n\nNorth Korea was one of the first countries to close borders due to COVID-19.<ref name=\"Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way\"/> The government has implemented widespread travel restrictions,<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\">{{cite news |last1=Shinkman |first1=Paul D. |title=North Korea Opens Borders to Aid Amid Coronavirus Threat |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-13/north-korea-opens-borders-to-aid-amid-coronavirus-threat |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> including closing the border to foreign tourists in late January<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\">{{cite news |title=North Korea Bars Foreign Tourists Amid Virus Threat, Groups Say |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-22/north-korea-bars-foreign-tourists-amid-virus-threat-groups-say |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=22 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and then suspending flights and banning travel in and out of the country.<ref name=\"Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way\">{{cite news |title=Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way |url=https://www.38north.org/2020/02/eimaabrahamian022020/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=38 North |date=20 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Though many parts of the border were closed, the bridge between [[Dandong]] and [[Sinuiju]] remained open and allowed supplies to be delivered.<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\">{{cite news |title=Russia Delivers Coronavirus Test Kits to North Korea |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-12/russia-delivers-coronavirus-test-kits-to-north-korea |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In late February, the North Korean government said that it would keep the border closed until a cure was found.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nThe possibility of a COVID-19 outbreak in North Korea is a concern to international organizations and observers due to the country's poverty and low-quality healthcare infrastructure. Outside organizations have provided aid to help the country fight the virus: the Russian government provided [[COVID-19 testing|test kits]],<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> the [[World Health Organization]] announced plans to send supplies despite the lack of confirmed cases, and the [[International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies]], [[U.S. State Department]], and South Korean government all indicated willingness to help.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> The U.S. government worked with the United Nations to make exceptions to sanctions, though they were also criticized for slowing down the process for providing aid.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/> [[Doctors Without Borders]] said in late March that supplies of diagnostic equipment and [[personal protective equipment]] were stranded on the Chinese border.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early February, the [[North Korean government]] took severe measures to block the spread of the coronavirus. ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'', the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] newspaper, reported that the customs officials at [[Nampho]] port were performing disinfection activities, including placing imported goods in quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://kcnawatch.org/newstream/1583703072-617647256/\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744-\uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c-\ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4-\uc5c6\uac8c/ |script-title=ko:\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744 \uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c \ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4 \uc5c6\uac8c |language=ko |date=2020-03-09 |accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref> All international flights and railway services were suspended in early February, and connections by sea and road were largely closed over the following weeks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February, wearing face masks was obligatory and visiting public places like restaurants was forbidden. Ski resorts and spas were closed, and military parades, marathons, and other public events were cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed throughout the country; university students in Pyongyang from elsewhere in the country were confined to their dormitories.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=Sources: N. Korea extends school closures until April 15 |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-north-korea-extends-school-closures-until-april-15/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\">{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=N. Korea closes schools throughout the country for one month |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-closes-schools-throughout-country-one-month/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korean citizens returning from other countries faced a 40-day isolation period to which was added a 30-day \u201cmedical observation\u201d period. According to North Korean media, nearly 7000 North Koreans were held under these rules at 1 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the North Korean government, 10,000 people had been quarantined by the end of March.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/> From 12 February, the 14-day quarantine on all foreigners (including their local staff) was extended to 30 days.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Diplomats and other foreigners were evacuated to [[Vladivostok]] in March.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/><ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> By 27 March, according to North Korean media, there were only two foreigners in quarantine and 2280 North Koreans were under \"medical observation\" in areas such as [[South Phyongan]] province and [[North Phyongan]] province, [[Ryanggang]] province, and the city of [[Rason]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe North Korean military fired five missiles on two occasions in early March 2020, which may be \"an effort to ensure the country remains on the agenda for other nations amid the virus outbreak\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> More missile tests followed in late March, along with an announcement that the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] would meet in early April. Foreign observers said the government was trying to show confidence in their handling of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Missile tests and meetings: North Korea signals confidence in face of coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-northkorea-analysi/missile-tests-and-meetings-north-korea-signals-confidence-in-face-of-coronavirus-idUSKBN21A0O7 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The South Korean military called the provocation \"extremely inappropriate\" in light of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea Fires Missile Into East Sea |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-28/north-korea-fires-missile-into-east-sea-s-korea-military-says |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, North Korea leader [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nKim Jong-un sent a letter to South Korean President [[Moon Jae-in]] as a show of support amidst the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|outbreak in South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Top U.S. Commander 'Fairly Certain' North Korea Has Virus Cases |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-14/top-u-s-commander-fairly-certain-north-korea-has-virus-cases |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=14 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] wrote a letter to [[Kim Jong-un]] to express his willingness to work with him on dealing with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea says Trump wrote Kim, offered coronavirus cooperation |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-northkorea-idUSKBN2180YX |work=Reuters |date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korean state media has reported on the severity of the outbreak in other countries.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/>\n\nOn 31 March 2020, the ''[[Asia Times]]'' reported that North Korea's measures against the pandemic seemed largely successful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/north-koreas-silent-struggle-against-covid-19/|title=North Korea\u2019s silent struggle against Covid-19|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 11, Kim Jong-un presided over a meeting of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]. The meeting adopted a joint resolution by the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]], [[State Affairs Commission of North Korea|State Affairs Commission]] and the [[Cabinet of North Korea|Cabinet]], \u201cOn more thoroughly taking national measures for protecting the life and safety of our people from the worldwide epidemic disease\u201d. The resolution called to take strict national countermeasures to thoroughly check the inroads of the virus due to the steady spread of the epidemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/04/kim-jong-un-guides-saturdays-politburo-meeting-ahead-of-spa-state-media/|title=North Korea\u2019s Politburo discusses \u201cdanger\u201d from COVID-19, promotes officials|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nAlthough South Korean media shared news hinting at the spread of the COVID-19 epidemic to North Korea, the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] denied the veracity of such claims. On 18 February, ''Rodong Sinmun'' quoted a public health official reiterating the country had had \"no confirmed case of the new coronavirus so far\". The WHO prioritised aid for North Korea, including the shipment of protective equipment and supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|title=World Health Organization says there are 'no indications' of coronavirus cases in North Korea|publisher=CNBC|date=19 February 2020|access-date=19 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219100113/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Military===\nIn early March, the North Korean government continued to deny that they had any cases of [[COVID-19]]. However, according to [[South Korea]]n media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'', 180 soldiers had died. There was no estimate of those merely infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3074377/coronavirus-nearly-200-north-korea-soldiers-die-outbreak|title=Coronavirus: nearly 200 North Korea soldiers 'die from outbreak government refuses to acknowledge'|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February and March, U.S. officials observed a decrease in military activity in North Korea, believed to be a sign that there are COVID-19 cases in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> General [[Robert B. Abrams]] observed that the North Korean military had \"been on lockdown for about 30 days\" and \"didn\u2019t fly an airplane for 24 days\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\n===Political===\nThe underground network that assists [[North Korean defectors|defectors in escaping North Korea]] has been almost unable to operate amidst strict controls implemented to stop the virus, with defection attempts being suspended.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\">{{cite news |title=Group of North Korean women and children escape coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.ft.com/content/253d5ff0-63e9-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.ft.com |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Defection rates had been declining already, probably due to increased security under the administrations of [[Kim Jong-un]] in North Korea and [[Xi Jinping]] in China.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\"/>\n\n===Economic===\nOn 26 March, the New York Times reported satellite imagery shared by the [[Royal United Services Institute]], which showed that the illicit trafficking of coal and other goods stopped, with the commercial vessels now idling in their home ports.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/video/coronavirus-north-korea.html</ref> This trafficking is prohibited under United Nations sanctions, and is believed to be mostly with China. The change happened after North Korea sought to seal itself off starting 22 January. These sales normally provide a revenue stream that has historically contributed to its nuclear and ballistic missile programs. It may also cause a possible drop in fuel and fertilizer imports, which would affect North Korea\u2019s agriculture sector, right at the beginning of the farming season. Analysts said it was reasonable to assume damage has been done to North Korean agriculture, industry and the overall economy.\n\n==Timeline==\n===January 2020===\nFrom 23 January, North Korea banned [[Tourism in North Korea|foreign tourists]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/north-korea-to-temporarily-ban-tourists-over-wuhan-virus-fears-says-tour-company|title=North Korea to temporarily ban tourists over Wuhan virus fears, says tour company|last=hermesauto|date=21 January 2020|website=The Straits Times|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, suspected cases in [[Sinuiju]] were quarantined.{{update inline|date=February 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|title=N. Korea quarantines suspected coronavirus cases in Sinuiju|website=Daily NK|date=28 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130223216/https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January, North Korea's news agency [[KCNA]] declared a \"state emergency\" and reported the establishment of anti-epidemic headquarters around the country.<ref name=\"20200206cnn\">{{cite news |last1=Berlinger |first1=Joshua |last2=Seo |first2=Yoonjung |title=All of its neighbors have it, so why hasn't North Korea reported any coronavirus cases? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207093221/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html |archive-date=7 February 2020 |accessdate=7 February 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 2 February, KCNA reported that all the people who had entered the country after 13 January were placed under \"medical supervision.\"<ref name=\"20200206cnn\"/>\n\nOn 7 February, South Korean media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'' claimed that five North Koreans in [[Sinuiju]] on the Chinese border died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|title=Sources: Five N. Koreans died from coronavirus infections|author=Jang Seul Gi|website=Daily NK|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082046/https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Within the same day, ''[[The Korea Times]]'' reported that a North Korean female living in the capital [[Pyongyang]] was infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|title=Coronavirus spreads to North Korea, woman infected|website=The Standard|location=Hong Kong|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082206/https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite no confirmation by North Korean authorities on the claims, the country has implemented stricter measures to combat the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pyongyangtimes.com.kp/?bbs=33091|title=Nation steps up fight against novel CoV|website=The Pyongyang Times|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rodong.rep.kp/en/index.php?strPageID=SF01_02_01&newsID=2020-02-08-0001|title=Work to Curb the Inflow of Infectious Disease Pushed ahead with|website=Rodong Sinmun|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed starting on 20 February.<ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\"/>\n\nOn 29 February, [[Kim Jong-un]] called for stronger measures to be taken to prevent COVID-19 from spreading to North Korea.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/kim-warns-consequences-virus-spreads-korea-200229061648473.html | title=Kim warns of 'serious consequences' if virus spreads to N Korea |work=al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 14 March 2020, North Korea state media reported there were no confirmed cases in its territory.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Stella |last2=Hagen |first2=Isobel |date=March 14, 2020 |title=North Korea claims it has no coronavirus cases |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/live-blog/coronavirus-updates-live-house-approves-coronavirus-aid-bill-n1158821/ncrd1158881#liveBlogHeader |work=NBC News |access-date=March 14, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals in North Korea. North Korean state media also reported that groundbreaking on a new hospital was underway the day prior on Tuesday 17 March. Kim Jong-un reportedly told a newspaper linked to the ruling [[Workers' Party of Korea]] that the construction of new hospitals were being done for general improvement of the nation's healthcare system without mentioning COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/kim-jong-un-north-korea-hospital-coronavirus |title = Kim Jong Un orders workers to build new hospitals as North Korea continues to claim no coronavirus cases |work=[[Fox News]] |date = 2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, North Korean media said that more than 2,590 people had been released from quarantine in [[North Pyongan]] and [[South Pyongan]] provinces. All but three quarantined foreigners had been released.<ref name=\"aa.com.tr 21\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19: North Korea releases quarantined people |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-north-korea-releases-quarantined-people/1773332 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April 2020, North Korean public health official Pak Myong Su repeated the claim that North Korea has no cases of the virus.<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\">{{cite news |title=N. Korea has no infected people with new coronavirus: expert |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200402/p2g/00m/0in/025000c |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Mainichi Daily News |date=2 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Health in North Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Medicine|North Korea|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2020 in North Korea|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in North Korea]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 pandemic in North Korea}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case = \n| location = [[North Korea]]\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| arrival_date =\n| image = \n| caption = \n| recovery_cases = \n| deaths =\n| confirmed_cases = 0 (disputed)\n| suspected_cases =\n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\n{{Politics of North Korea|width=22.0em}}\n\nThere are no officially confirmed cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[North Korea]], although South Korean sources say that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the pandemic]] is steadily affecting the country. The virus is more likely to have come into North Korea from [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]], where the virus originates, than from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]]. The [[China\u2013North Korea border|Chinese-North Korean border]] restrictions are more relaxed than the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone|heavily militarized border]] between North and South Korea. However, suspected COVID-19 cases in the two Chinese provinces ([[Liaoning]] and [[Jilin]]) bordering North Korea have been low.<ref name=\"Who Knows\">{{Cite web |title=Who Knows How Many Virus Cases North Korea Has. It Says Zero |last1=Wainer |first1=David |last2=Lee |first2=Jihye |work=Bloomberg.com |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/north-korea-s-official-virus-tally-zero-experts-aren-t-so-sure }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nNorth Korea is an impoverished country with a weak healthcare system and [[Sanctions against North Korea|is subject to sanctions]], making it vulnerable in the event of an outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Korea says detected North Korea missile fire 'inapproriate' amid coronavirus |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/21/north-korea-fired-suspected-short-range-missiles-south-korea-says.html |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> There is concern that widespread malnutrition could worsen the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> North Korean public health official Pak Myong Su said that if the disease spread in North Korea, \"a serious disaster could not be avoided\".<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\"/>\n\nDiplomatically and economically isolated,<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> the country borders China, the starting point of the pandemic, which is North Korea's closest ally, most important trading partner, and a source of tourists.<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/><ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\">{{cite news |last1=Sang-Hun |first1=Choe |title=North Korea Claims No Coronavirus Cases. Can It Be Trusted? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/world/asia/north-korea-coronavirus.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korea's government is secretive and the media are tightly controlled, making it hard for outside observers to determine what is really going on in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\nHistorically, North Korea has cut off travel in the face of epidemics abroad, for instance during the [[2014 Ebola epidemic]].<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\"/> Moreover, the country has had success in disease eradication in the past; it reportedly eliminated [[measles]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Minal K. |title=Progress Toward Regional Measles Elimination \u2014 Worldwide, 2000\u20132018 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/68/wr/mm6848a1.htm |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |date=2019 |language=en-us |doi=10.15585/mmwr.mm6848a1}}</ref><ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> North Korea's government is highly [[authoritarian]] and maintains strong control over the country, which experts anticipated could help in enforcing disease control measures such as [[social distancing]].<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Why North Korea's healthcare sector is better equipped than many believe |url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/why-north-koreas-healthcare-sector-is-better-equipped-than-many-believe/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=NK News - North Korea News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> North Korea also has a large number of doctors, though they are less skilled and equipped than their Western counterparts, and a high level of public hygiene.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why North Korea's healthcare sector is better equipped than many believe |url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/why-north-koreas-healthcare-sector-is-better-equipped-than-many-believe/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=NK News - North Korea News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\n[[File:Masikryong-Hotel-and-Lift.jpg|200px|thumb|left|[[Masikryong Ski Resort]], a popular ski resort in North Korea. Due to the outbreak of the virus, ski resorts and spas in North Korea have been closed.]]\n\nNorth Korea was one of the first countries to close borders due to COVID-19.<ref name=\"Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way\"/> The government has implemented widespread travel restrictions,<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\">{{cite news |last1=Shinkman |first1=Paul D. |title=North Korea Opens Borders to Aid Amid Coronavirus Threat |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-13/north-korea-opens-borders-to-aid-amid-coronavirus-threat |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> including closing the border to foreign tourists in late January<ref name=\"bars foreign tourists\">{{cite news |title=North Korea Bars Foreign Tourists Amid Virus Threat, Groups Say |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-22/north-korea-bars-foreign-tourists-amid-virus-threat-groups-say |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=22 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and then suspending flights and banning travel in and out of the country.<ref name=\"Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way\">{{cite news |title=Pandemics and Preparation the North Korean Way |url=https://www.38north.org/2020/02/eimaabrahamian022020/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=38 North |date=20 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Though many parts of the border were closed, the bridge between [[Dandong]] and [[Sinuiju]] remained open and allowed supplies to be delivered.<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\">{{cite news |title=Russia Delivers Coronavirus Test Kits to North Korea |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world-report/articles/2020-03-12/russia-delivers-coronavirus-test-kits-to-north-korea |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> In late February, the North Korean government said that it would keep the border closed until a cure was found.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\"/>\n\nThe possibility of a COVID-19 outbreak in North Korea is a concern to international organizations and observers due to the country's poverty and low-quality healthcare infrastructure. Outside organizations have provided aid to help the country fight the virus: the Russian government provided [[COVID-19 testing|test kits]],<ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> the [[World Health Organization]] announced plans to send supplies despite the lack of confirmed cases, and the [[International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies]], [[U.S. State Department]], and South Korean government all indicated willingness to help.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> The U.S. government worked with the United Nations to make exceptions to sanctions, though they were also criticized for slowing down the process for providing aid.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/> [[Doctors Without Borders]] said in late March that supplies of diagnostic equipment and [[personal protective equipment]] were stranded on the Chinese border.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early February, the [[North Korean government]] took severe measures to block the spread of the coronavirus. ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'', the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] newspaper, reported that the customs officials at [[Nampho]] port were performing disinfection activities, including placing imported goods in quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://kcnawatch.org/newstream/1583703072-617647256/\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744-\uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c-\ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4-\uc5c6\uac8c/ |script-title=ko:\uac80\uc0ac\uac80\uc5ed\uc744 \uc0ac\uc18c\ud55c \ube48\ud2c8\ub3c4 \uc5c6\uac8c |language=ko |date=2020-03-09 |accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref> All international flights and railway services were suspended in early February, and connections by sea and road were largely closed over the following weeks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February, wearing face masks was obligatory and visiting public places like restaurants was forbidden. Ski resorts and spas were closed, and military parades, marathons, and other public events were cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed throughout the country; university students in Pyongyang from elsewhere in the country were confined to their dormitories.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=Sources: N. Korea extends school closures until April 15 |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-north-korea-extends-school-closures-until-april-15/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\">{{cite news |last1=Joo |first1=Jeong Tae |title=N. Korea closes schools throughout the country for one month |url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-closes-schools-throughout-country-one-month/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Daily NK |date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korean citizens returning from other countries faced a 40-day isolation period to which was added a 30-day \u201cmedical observation\u201d period. According to North Korean media, nearly 7000 North Koreans were held under these rules at 1 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the North Korean government, 10,000 people had been quarantined by the end of March.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/> From 12 February, the 14-day quarantine on all foreigners (including their local staff) was extended to 30 days.<ref name=\"covid-19 overview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/covid-19-in-north-korea-an-overview-of-the-current-situation/?t=1585236870435|title=COVID-19 in North Korea: an overview of the current situation|first=Chad|last=O'Carroll|publisher=NK News|date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Diplomats and other foreigners were evacuated to [[Vladivostok]] in March.<ref name=\"North Korea Opens Borders\"/><ref name=\"Russia Delivers\"/> By 27 March, according to North Korean media, there were only two foreigners in quarantine and 2280 North Koreans were under \"medical observation\" in areas such as [[South Phyongan]] province and [[North Phyongan]] province, [[Ryanggang]] province, and the city of [[Rason]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/03/two-foreigners-left-under-quarantine-in-north-korea-state-media/?t=1585324059464|title=Only two foreigners remain under quarantine in North Korea, state media says|first=Jeongmin|last=Kim|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe North Korean military fired five missiles on two occasions in early March 2020, which may be \"an effort to ensure the country remains on the agenda for other nations amid the virus outbreak\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> More missile tests followed in late March, along with an announcement that the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] would meet in early April. Foreign observers said the government was trying to show confidence in their handling of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Missile tests and meetings: North Korea signals confidence in face of coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-northkorea-analysi/missile-tests-and-meetings-north-korea-signals-confidence-in-face-of-coronavirus-idUSKBN21A0O7 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The South Korean military called the provocation \"extremely inappropriate\" in light of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea Fires Missile Into East Sea |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-28/north-korea-fires-missile-into-east-sea-s-korea-military-says |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, North Korea leader [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nKim Jong-un sent a letter to South Korean President [[Moon Jae-in]] as a show of support amidst the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|outbreak in South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Top U.S. Commander 'Fairly Certain' North Korea Has Virus Cases |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-14/top-u-s-commander-fairly-certain-north-korea-has-virus-cases |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=14 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] wrote a letter to [[Kim Jong-un]] to express his willingness to work with him on dealing with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea says Trump wrote Kim, offered coronavirus cooperation |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-northkorea-idUSKBN2180YX |work=Reuters |date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nNorth Korean state media has reported on the severity of the outbreak in other countries.<ref name=\"North Korea Claims 2020-03-31\"/>\n\nOn 31 March 2020, the ''[[Asia Times]]'' reported that North Korea's measures against the pandemic seemed largely successful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/north-koreas-silent-struggle-against-covid-19/|title=North Korea\u2019s silent struggle against Covid-19|first=Gabriela|last=Bernal|publisher=Asian Times|date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nAlthough South Korean media shared news hinting at the spread of the COVID-19 epidemic to North Korea, the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] denied the veracity of such claims. On 18 February, ''Rodong Sinmun'' quoted a public health official reiterating the country had had \"no confirmed case of the new coronavirus so far\". The WHO prioritised aid for North Korea, including the shipment of protective equipment and supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|title=World Health Organization says there are 'no indications' of coronavirus cases in North Korea|publisher=CNBC|date=19 February 2020|access-date=19 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219100113/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/who-says-no-signs-of-coronavirus-cases-in-north-korea.html|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Military===\nIn early March, the North Korean government continued to deny that they had any cases of [[COVID-19]]. However, according to [[South Korea]]n media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'', 180 soldiers had died. There was no estimate of those merely infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3074377/coronavirus-nearly-200-north-korea-soldiers-die-outbreak|title=Coronavirus: nearly 200 North Korea soldiers 'die from outbreak government refuses to acknowledge'|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February and March, U.S. officials observed a decrease in military activity in North Korea, believed to be a sign that there are COVID-19 cases in the country.<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/> General [[Robert B. Abrams]] observed that the North Korean military had \"been on lockdown for about 30 days\" and \"didn\u2019t fly an airplane for 24 days\".<ref name=\"Who Knows\"/>\n\n===Political===\nThe underground network that assists [[North Korean defectors|defectors in escaping North Korea]] has been almost unable to operate amidst strict controls implemented to stop the virus, with defection attempts being suspended.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\">{{cite news |title=Group of North Korean women and children escape coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.ft.com/content/253d5ff0-63e9-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.ft.com |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Defection rates had been declining already, probably due to increased security under the administrations of [[Kim Jong-un]] in North Korea and [[Xi Jinping]] in China.<ref name=\"Group of North Korean women and children\"/>\n\n===Economic===\nOn 26 March, the New York Times reported satellite imagery shared by the [[Royal United Services Institute]], which showed that the illicit trafficking of coal and other goods stopped, with the commercial vessels now idling in their home ports.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/video/coronavirus-north-korea.html</ref> This trafficking is prohibited under United Nations sanctions, and is believed to be mostly with China. The change happened after North Korea sought to seal itself off starting 22 January. These sales normally provide a revenue stream that has historically contributed to its nuclear and ballistic missile programs. It may also cause a possible drop in fuel and fertilizer imports, which would affect North Korea\u2019s agriculture sector, right at the beginning of the farming season. Analysts said it was reasonable to assume damage has been done to North Korean agriculture, industry and the overall economy.\n\n==Timeline==\n===January 2020===\nFrom 23 January, North Korea banned [[Tourism in North Korea|foreign tourists]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/north-korea-to-temporarily-ban-tourists-over-wuhan-virus-fears-says-tour-company|title=North Korea to temporarily ban tourists over Wuhan virus fears, says tour company|last=hermesauto|date=21 January 2020|website=The Straits Times|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, suspected cases in [[Sinuiju]] were quarantined.{{update inline|date=February 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|title=N. Korea quarantines suspected coronavirus cases in Sinuiju|website=Daily NK|date=28 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130223216/https://www.dailynk.com/english/north-korea-quarantines-suspected-coronavirus-cases-sinuiju/|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January, North Korea's news agency [[KCNA]] declared a \"state emergency\" and reported the establishment of anti-epidemic headquarters around the country.<ref name=\"20200206cnn\">{{cite news |last1=Berlinger |first1=Joshua |last2=Seo |first2=Yoonjung |title=All of its neighbors have it, so why hasn't North Korea reported any coronavirus cases? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207093221/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/06/asia/north-korea-wuhan-coronavirus-infection-intl-hnk/index.html |archive-date=7 February 2020 |accessdate=7 February 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 2 February, KCNA reported that all the people who had entered the country after 13 January were placed under \"medical supervision.\"<ref name=\"20200206cnn\"/>\n\nOn 7 February, South Korean media outlet ''[[Daily NK]]'' claimed that five North Koreans in [[Sinuiju]] on the Chinese border died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|title=Sources: Five N. Koreans died from coronavirus infections|author=Jang Seul Gi|website=Daily NK|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082046/https://www.dailynk.com/english/sources-five-north-koreans-died-coronavirus-infections/|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Within the same day, ''[[The Korea Times]]'' reported that a North Korean female living in the capital [[Pyongyang]] was infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|title=Coronavirus spreads to North Korea, woman infected|website=The Standard|location=Hong Kong|date=7 February 2020|access-date=8 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208082206/https://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news/section/3/141479/Coronavirus-spreads-to-North-Korea,-woman-infected|archive-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite no confirmation by North Korean authorities on the claims, the country has implemented stricter measures to combat the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pyongyangtimes.com.kp/?bbs=33091|title=Nation steps up fight against novel CoV|website=The Pyongyang Times|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rodong.rep.kp/en/index.php?strPageID=SF01_02_01&newsID=2020-02-08-0001|title=Work to Curb the Inflow of Infectious Disease Pushed ahead with|website=Rodong Sinmun|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed starting on 20 February.<ref name=\"N Korea closes schools\"/>\n\nOn 29 February, [[Kim Jong-un]] called for stronger measures to be taken to prevent COVID-19 from spreading to North Korea.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/kim-warns-consequences-virus-spreads-korea-200229061648473.html | title=Kim warns of 'serious consequences' if virus spreads to N Korea |work=al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 14 March 2020, North Korea state media reported there were no confirmed cases in its territory.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Stella |last2=Hagen |first2=Isobel |date=March 14, 2020 |title=North Korea claims it has no coronavirus cases |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/live-blog/coronavirus-updates-live-house-approves-coronavirus-aid-bill-n1158821/ncrd1158881#liveBlogHeader |work=NBC News |access-date=March 14, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2020, [[Kim Jong-un]] ordered the construction of new hospitals in North Korea. North Korean state media also reported that groundbreaking on a new hospital was underway the day prior on Tuesday 17 March. Kim Jong-un reportedly told a newspaper linked to the ruling [[Workers' Party of Korea]] that the construction of new hospitals were being done for general improvement of the nation's healthcare system without mentioning COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/kim-jong-un-north-korea-hospital-coronavirus |title = Kim Jong Un orders workers to build new hospitals as North Korea continues to claim no coronavirus cases |work=[[Fox News]] |date = 2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, North Korean media said that more than 2,590 people had been released from quarantine in [[North Pyongan]] and [[South Pyongan]] provinces. All but three quarantined foreigners had been released.<ref name=\"aa.com.tr 21\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19: North Korea releases quarantined people |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-north-korea-releases-quarantined-people/1773332 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April 2020, North Korean public health official Pak Myong Su repeated the claim that North Korea has no cases of the virus.<ref name=\"Mainichi 2 April\">{{cite news |title=N. Korea has no infected people with new coronavirus: expert |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200402/p2g/00m/0in/025000c |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Mainichi Daily News |date=2 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Health in North Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Medicine|North Korea|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|North Korea]]\n[[Category:2020 in North Korea|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in North Korea]]\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResponse", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_North_Korea"}
